Facial Emotion Detection¶

Submission by Alexander J Miller¶

Problem and Solution Summary¶

  • Problem to be Solved
    • Emotion detection has all sorts of applications, we are specifically interested in how recognition of facial expressions can assist in deception detection and information gain for law enforcement purposes. Facial expressions, among many other behaviors, can provide insight into what someone is thinking or feeling. Properly recognizing and reacting to such expressions can help law enforcement identify areas for follow up and recognize when they may not be getting the whole story.
    • As with may other tasks, humans are prone to bias and emotion which can influence their ability to recognize and react to behavioral queues (like facial expressions), for this reason a computer model could be a helpful tool in the consistent and effective identification of such behaviors.
    • Such a tool could function as a 'gut check' or a second opinion in addition to helping identify details/behaviors an individual may have missed

  • Proposed Solution

    • This project serves as a proof of concept to show that computers are capable of such tasks by proving they are capable of detecting 4 basic emotions: happy, sad, neutral and surprise.
    • We have designed and trained a convolutionl neural network to classify images of faces. The model was able to achieve 83% accuracy on the given test data, and this can very likely be improved upon.
    • almost all models had gret difficulty exceeding 70% - 75% accuracy on the test data. Data augmentation was vital in getting the accuracy over 80%, indicating greater data/diversity would be substantially beneficial
    • precision was the lowest for 'neutral' images at 73%, and recall was the lowest for 'sad' images at 71%.
    • the final model consisted of 58 layers: 32 convolutional layers, a flatten layer, 24 ANN lyers and an output layer

    • for the most part the CNN consisted of repeated 'substructures' of the following form:

      model.add(Conv2D([# of filters], ([kernal size]), padding="same", activation = 'relu'))

      model.add(BatchNormalization())

      model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))

      model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))

      model.add(Dropout(.2))

    • most of the ANN consisted of repeated 'substructures' of the following form:

      model.add(Dense([# of nodes], activation = 'relu'))

      model.add(BatchNormalization())

      model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))

      model.add(Dropout(.2))

    • these substructures provided a manageable/organized way to add complexity to the model without having to fret over ll the different sorts of changes that could be made. However, this overreliance on the 'substructure' strategy also provides an area for further exploration as there is no reason to assume this is the most effective strategy, it was merely convenient for building the models

Executive Summary¶

  • Key Takeaways
    • Based on the findings in the following notebook it is clear that effective facial emotion recognition by a CNN is very possible.
    • the best model we were able to implement (cnn_model_3c2) achieved an accuracy of 83% on the provided test data, this can almost certainly be improved upon with further experimentation.
    • transfer learning attempts proved ineffective as the "learnings" of the trained models did not seem to carry over well to our specific use case. We tested the VGG16, ResNet and EfficientNet pre-trained models. Performance was poor, but this does not rule out the possibility that other pre-trained models exist which could prove effective at emotion recognition.
    • there is a clear need for more data (i.e. more images). Any emotion has a diverse spectrum regarding how it may appear or be exhibited by an individual. To combat this there is a need for more images, the more images we have the more likely we are to capture the full spectrum of the many ways any one emotion may be exhibited.
  • Next Steps
    • procure more images! Access to the 420,000+ images of the AffectNet database could be immensely helpful (http://mohammadmahoor.com/affectnet/); however, access has to be requested and granted (and seems to be reserved for students, professors, or lab managers). There are certainly other databases worth exploring as well
    • further emotions need to be added to the model/data. Anger, disgust and fear are crutial emotions that can be very informative. These would need to be added to any model designed to assist in deception detection and information gathering
    • the model needs to then be implemented to utilize a video feed as opposed to being fed individual images
    • finally, to be maximally useful, our model should be able to identify behaviors that go beyond facial emotions. Behaviors like touching the face, swallowing, pausing and failing to answer questions can all be very informative. They go well beyond the scope of this project, but identifying such behaviors would be significant and could go a long way to assist in deception detection and information gain.

Recommendations for Implementation¶

  • Key Risks
    • the model is able to recognize emotions only, it is unable to make any judgements about what they may mean or take their context into account
    • this model is intended to assist with information gathering and deception detection, it is a tool to be utilized by an experienced professional who should exercise their own judgement accordingly

  • Implementation

    • Microsoft Azure has an array of services available specifically for housing and training machine learning models.
    • they will store 1,000 faces for \$.01 per month
    • they have an API platform for deep learning applications geared towards working with facial images charging:

    0-1M transactions - \$1 per 1,000 transactions

    1-10M transactions - \$0.65 per 1,000 transactions

    10-100M transactions - \$0.60 per 1,000 transactions

    100M+ transactions - \$0.40 per 1,000 transactions

    • pricing is application specific and a proper quote would need to be obtained for more accurate pricing depending on the model's implementation (https://azure.microsoft.com/en-us/pricing/details/cognitive-services/)
  • Further Analysis
    • there is still a significant amount of experimentation to be performed in order to improve the model.
    • We have barely scratched the surface of all sorts of parameters. For instance activation functions were barely tweaked and loss functions were never altered. Batch sizes were never adjusted nor were step sizes.
    • checkpoints should be utilized going forward! Checkpoints can be used to save the best performing models, which is imperative as I have lost models due to Colab timing out! This will also help with identifying the best models over a series of epochs, currently I have am left with single model after training over a given number of epochs. This means I could be missing out on better models if they occur during the training period (such models would be lost but checkpoints would be able to identify and save such models)
    • the numer of epochs to train over should also be experimented with. The best model was trained for 75 epochs on original images and then 75, 75 and 100 epochs on augmented images. These numbers were arbitrary and should be tweaked to see what gives the best performance. I also trained the model for 40 epochs on original images and then groups of 40 epochs on augmented images, getting up to 320 epochs. However, thi number of epochs seems to have been too low for meaningful learning to take place fir a given dataset and accuracy on validation data (once again) capped out around 70% - 75%.
    • an effort should be made to add images to our datasets. The alternative dataset I utilized (from kaggle) had a substantial amount of overlap with the provided dataset, but there were still 5,000 or so unique images that coud have been utilized and were not. Moreover, there are plenty of repositories for labeled facial expression images o the internet that are worth looking into.
    • More images coud have a substantial impact on image accuracy. It seems that the difficulty in exceeding 70% - 75% accuracy on the validation data is simply because any single emotion has a very diverse number of possible apperances. Data augmentation helped to add some variation into our dataset (and capture some of this diversity), but additional images would be far more valuable!
    • As mentioned above, adjusting the model to utilize a video feed and identifying actions like touching the face, swallowing and coughing would be an important avenue to explore for the next iteration of a model to identify deception and facilitate information gathering.

Problem Definition¶

The context: Why is this problem important to solve?

  • a model that can detect facial emotions could give us insight into how people are feeling or what they might be thinking. This could be used to gauge how people respond to products, ads, sales pitches, etc. In our case, emotion recognition to assist law enforcement with deception detection and information gathering is the specific use case we are interested in.

The objectives: What is the intended goal?

  • given an image of a face have a model correctly classify the face as happy, sad, neutral or surprised

The key questions: What are the key questions that need to be answered?

  • what are the distinguishing characteristics of each emotion? Can a model recognize these?
  • is our data optimal? do imperfections exist like duplicate or mislabeled images?

The problem formulation: What are we trying to solve using data science?

  • this is a supervised learning, classification problem with 4 classes
  • using convolutional neural networks we will attempt to create a model that can correctly identify and classify happy, sad, neutral and surprised faces.

About the dataset¶

The data set consists of 3 folders, i.e., 'test', 'train', and 'validation'. Each of these folders has four subfolders:

happy: Images of people who have happy facial expressions.
sad: Images of people with sad or upset facial expressions.
surprise: Images of people who have shocked or surprised facial expressions.
neutral: Images of people showing no prominent emotion in their facial expression at all.

# Storing the path of the data file from the Google drive
path = '/content/drive/MyDrive/MIT_DataScience/Capstone Project/Facial_emotion_images.zip'

# The data is provided as a zip file so we need to extract the files from the zip file
with zipfile.ZipFile(path, 'r') as zip_ref:
    zip_ref.extractall()
In [ ]:
# set data folder path so it can be easily referenced
folder_path = "Facial_emotion_images/"
In [ ]:
# create dataframe to store images and relevant features
image_df = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['emotion', 'data type', 'path', 'image','image hash','pixel data rgb','pixel data gray'])

counter = 0

data_type_path = os.listdir(folder_path)

# get each data type folder (ie. training, validation, test)
for data_type in data_type_path:
  emotion_type_path = os.listdir(folder_path + data_type )
  # get each emotion type folder (ie. happy, sad, neutral, surprise)
  for emotion in emotion_type_path:
    image_path = os.listdir(folder_path +  data_type + '/' + emotion)
    for face_image in image_path:
      # get the path for an individual image
      path_of_image = folder_path + data_type +'/'+  emotion + '/' + face_image

      # load the image, as color and grayscale image
      img_rgb = load_img(folder_path + data_type +'/'+  emotion + '/' + face_image, color_mode='rgb')
      img_gray = load_img(folder_path + data_type +'/'+  emotion + '/' + face_image, color_mode='grayscale')

      # this will assign a unique hash to every image (which we will use to check for duplicates)
      image_hash = imagehash.average_hash(img_gray)

      #convert color and grayscale images into separate pixel arrays
      pixel_array_rgb = img_to_array(img_rgb)
      pixel_array_gray = img_to_array(img_gray)

      # add path, emotion type and data type into a dataframe
      image_df = image_df.append({'emotion' : emotion, 'data type' : data_type, 'path' : path_of_image,"image":img_rgb,'image hash':image_hash, 'pixel data rgb':pixel_array_rgb, 'pixel data gray':pixel_array_gray},ignore_index = True)

image_num = 0
greyscale=True
for image in image_df['pixel data rgb']:
  for row in image:
    for pixel in row:
      if (pixel[0] == pixel[1] == pixel[2]) != True:
        #this will print out the path to any image that contains colored pixels
        print(image_df['path'][image_num])
  image_num +=1

Are there duplicate images?¶

In [ ]:
# dropping all duplicate values based on repeat hashcodes
image_df.drop_duplicates(subset="image hash",keep=False, inplace=True)
image_df.shape
Out[ ]:
(18124, 7)

Observations:

  • there were 1146 different images which were features in the dataset more than once. They have been deleted
  • we now have a dataset consisting of 18,124 unique images
  • this will help to remove bias from the data (which might help reduce overfitting) as well as reduce information leaks between training, validation and testing datasets
  • it is worth noting that this only removes EXACT duplicates. Some images could look identical but have a few differing pixels, such images would still be contianed in the dataset. Therefore, we cannot be certain that all duplicates have been removed

Visualizing our Classes¶

Let's look at our classes.

Write down your observation for each class. What do you think can be a unique feature of each emotion, that separates it from the remaining classes?

In [ ]:
# set the size for an image
picture_size = 48

# define a function to display 9 images (in the training set) of a given emotion
def displayImageSample(expression):
  plt.figure(figsize= (8,8))
  for i in range(1, 10, 1):
      plt.subplot(3, 3, i)

      #load the image
      img = load_img(folder_path + "train/" + expression + "/" + os.listdir(folder_path + "train/" + expression)[i], target_size = (picture_size, picture_size))

      # remove tickmarks and text
      ax = plt.gca()
      ax.tick_params('y', labelleft=False)
      ax.tick_params('x', labelbottom=False)
      ax.set_xticks(ticks=[])
      ax.set_yticks(ticks=[])
      plt.imshow(img)

  plt.show()

Happy¶

In [ ]:
# display nine images labeled 'happy' (from the training set)
displayImageSample('happy')

Observations and Insights: happy

  • faces depicted in these images tend to show teeth and tend to squint due to raised cheeks
  • the corners of the mouth pull back towards the ears
  • these features seem prominant enough that our model should be able to recognize them

Sad¶

In [ ]:
# display nine images labeled 'sad' (from the training set)
displayImageSample('sad')

Observations and Insights: sad

  • faces depicted tend to have a furrowed brow and outer eyebrows slanting downward
  • subjects depicted seem to have a greater liklihood to 'avert their gaze' (look down or to the side) when compared to other emotions
  • some face exhibit a classic 'frown,' but not all, suggesting this may be a misleading feature to look for
  • features are more subtle and more diverse than happiness, suggesting it will be more difficult to correctly recognize sadness as an emotion

Neutral¶

In [ ]:
# display nine images labeled 'neutral' (from the training set)

Observations and Insights: neutral

  • this wil likely be the most difficult emotion to correctly identify
  • there a few notable features, and it seems like the emotion is characterized moreso by a lack of distinguishable features
  • some of these faces look anxious, sad or happy. Correctly identifying neutral faces might be difficult for any model (maybe even a human in some instances!) Alternatively, this could be evidence that some images are mislabeled!

Reducing the Number of 'Happy' Images in the Validation Set¶

we will reduce the number of 'happy' images in the validation set to 1122 (the mean of the number of sad and neutral images in the validation set)

In [ ]:
index_list = []
to_remove = 0

# get emotion column from validation_data_df and convert it to a numpy array
data = validation_data_df['emotion'].to_numpy()

# loop through array of emotions, record the index of the first 648 'happy' images
for i in range(0,len(data)):
  if data[i] == 'happy' and to_remove < 648:
    index_list.append(i)
    to_remove+=1
In [ ]:
# reset indecies of validation_data_df so that the dataframes' indecies line up with indecies in index_list
validation_data_df = validation_data_df.reset_index()
validation_data_df = validation_data_df.drop(index = index_list)

Think About It:

  • Are the classes equally distributed? If not, do you think the imbalance is too high? Will it be a problem as we progress?
  • Are there any Exploratory Data Analysis tasks that we can do here? Would they provide any meaningful insights?

Responses:

  • in all three data sets, surprise is featured significantly less than the other emotions, however there is no reason to assume that this is an underrepresentation. Since surprise has fewer occurances in all datasets it could be the case that it is a less common emotion. Happy, neutral and sad have a similar number of occurences in all datasets except the validation data. Happiness is overrepresented in the validation data (accordingly we have decreased the number of happy images featured in the validation set).

  • there is not a ton of EDA to be done here. Since we are given raw images to work with it does not make sense to try and identify features or relationships between data points. However, there is still some level of exploration (some of which we did above) to extract data from images to learn about and improve the datasets.

Creating our Data Loaders¶

In this section, we are creating data loaders that we will use as inputs to our Neural Network.

You have two options for the color_mode. You can set it to color_mode = 'rgb' or color_mode = 'grayscale'. You will need to try out both and see for yourself which one gives better performance.

  • all images have already been loaded into the image dataframe with color_mode='grayscale'
  • this was done because all images in the dataset are already grayscale images
  • loading the images as color images would create redundant datapoints that would only slow down the training process
In [ ]:
# get datasets from respective dataframes/columns and convert data to a nummpy array for simplified usage and proper shape
x_train = []
x_val = []
x_test = []

for image in train_data_df['pixel data gray']:
  x_train.append(image)

for image in validation_data_df['pixel data gray']:
  x_val.append(image)

for image in test_data_df['pixel data gray']:
  x_test.append(image)

# 'GRAY' for grayscale images

x_val_GRAY = np.array(x_val)
x_test_GRAY = np.array(x_test)

  x_val.append(image)

# 'RGB' for RGB images

Model Building¶

Think About It:

  • Are Convolutional Neural Networks the right approach? Should we have gone with Artificial Neural Networks instead?
  • What are the advantages of CNNs over ANNs and are they applicable here?

Responses:

  • Convolutional Neural Networks are likely the right approach given that we are dealing with images
  • CNN's include additional convoutional layers that will help to process and find trends in the pixel data
  • we will not have to flatten images when passing them into a CNN, preserving the data/information

Defining Functions for Building, Training and Evaluating Models¶

In [ ]:
# define a function to clear backend and fix the seed for random number generators
def reset_environment():
  backend.clear_session()
  np.random.seed(random_seed_val)
  random.seed(random_seed_val)
  tf.random.set_seed(random_seed_val)
In [ ]:
# define a function to train a model for a given number of epochs on either RGB or GRAYSCALE images
def train_model(model, epochs, color_mode):

  # reset backend and random seed
  reset_environment()

  if color_mode == 'GRAY':
    # Fit given test_model on the GRAYSCALE images
    model_history = model.fit(
                x_train_norm_GRAY, y_train_encoded,
                epochs = epochs,
                batch_size= 32,
                validation_data = (x_val_norm_GRAY, y_val_encoded),
                verbose = 1
                )
    return model_history
  elif color_mode == 'RGB':
    # Fit given model on the RGB images
    model_history = model.fit(
                x_train_norm_RGB, y_train_encoded,
                epochs = epochs,
                batch_size= 32,
                validation_data = (x_val_norm_RGB,y_val_encoded),
                verbose = 1
                )
    return model_history
  else:
    print('ERROR - model not trained...')
    print('color_mode must be passed as GRAY or RGB')
In [ ]:
# define a function to plot validation accuracies of given trianing history
def plot_model(model_history, color_mode):
  if color_mode == 'GRAY':
    # plot trainging vs validation accuracy on GRAYSCALE images
    plt.plot(model_history.history['accuracy'])
    plt.plot(model_history.history['val_accuracy'])
    plt.title('Model Accuracy - Grayscale Images')
    plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')
    plt.legend(['Train', 'Validation'], loc = 'upper left')
    # Display the plot
    plt.show()
  elif color_mode == 'RGB':
    # plot trainging vs validation accuracy on RGB images
    plt.plot(model_history.history['accuracy'])
    plt.plot(model_history.history['val_accuracy'])
    plt.title('Model Accuracy - RGB Images')
    plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')
    plt.legend(['Train', 'Validation'], loc = 'upper left')
    # Display the plot
    plt.show()
  else:
    print('ERROR - color_mode must be passed s RGB or GRAY')

# define a function to test a model on the test data and print a classification report
def test_model(model, color_mode):
  if color_mode == 'GRAY':
    # see how the given test_model performs on the GRAYSCALE test data\
    y_pred=model.predict(x_test_norm_GRAY)
    y_pred_arg=np.argmax(y_pred,axis=1)
    y_test_arg=np.argmax(y_test_encoded,axis=1)
    #this will provide a key to make it clear which numbers refer to which classes
    print(emotion_dict)
    #Accuracy as per the classification report
    cr=metrics.classification_report(y_test_arg,y_pred_arg)
    print(cr)
  elif color_mode=='RGB':
    # see how the given test_model performs on the GRAYSCALE test data\
    y_pred=model.predict(x_test_norm_RGB)
    y_pred_arg=np.argmax(y_pred,axis=1)
    y_test_arg=np.argmax(y_test_encoded,axis=1)
    #this will provide a key to make it clear which numbers refer to which classes
    print(emotion_dict)
    #Accuracy as per the classification report
    cr=metrics.classification_report(y_test_arg,y_pred_arg)
    print(cr)
  else:
    print('ERROR - color_mode must be passed as RGB or GRAY')

Creating the Base Neural Network¶

In [ ]:
def cnn_model_1(shape_of_input):
  # Intializing a sequential model
  model1 = Sequential()

  model1.add(Conv2D(24, (4, 4), padding="same", input_shape=shape_of_input))
  model1.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model1.add(Conv2D(48, (4, 4), padding="same"))
  model1.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model1.add(MaxPooling2D((3, 3)))

  # flattening the output of the conv layer after max pooling to make it ready for creating dense connections
  model1.add(Flatten())

  # Adding a fully connected dense layer with 100 neurons
  model1.add(Dense(100))
  # Adding a fully connected dense layer with 100 neurons
  model1.add(Dense(100))
  # Adding the output layer with 4 neurons and activation functions as softmax since this is a 4 class classification problem
  model1.add(Dense(4, activation='softmax'))

  # Compile model
  model1.compile(loss = 'categorical_crossentropy',
              metrics = ['accuracy'],
              optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.001))

  return model1

Observations and Insights: cnn_model_1

  • this model is severely overfit, with almost 100% accuracy on the training data, but accuracy on the validation data remaining below 60% -using rgb vs greyscale images appears to have had little impact on performance, it did not affect training times either
  • the model does not appear to be learning as the validation accuracy does not improve with additional epochs
  • we should decrease the number of epochs and make incremental adjustments to the model until we observe signs of learning

Adjusting The Base Neural Network¶

We will implement many different convolutional modes/layers later on, so for now let's focus on the base neural network on its own (the ANN that our CNN models will work on top of). Lets try to adjust the ANN portion of our model to find an optimal base NN to add different CNNs to. We are already overfit, so we will focus solely on trying to improve validation accuracies. We will also only test on grayscale images to save time.

In [ ]:
def cnn_model_1a():
# this part to remain the same =====================================================================
  model1 = Sequential()
  model1.add(Conv2D(24, (4, 4), padding="same", input_shape=(48, 48, 1)))
  model1.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model1.add(Conv2D(48, (4, 4), padding="same"))
  model1.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model1.add(MaxPooling2D((3, 3)))
  model1.add(Flatten())
# ^this part to remain the same ^ ==================================================================

  # increase number of nodes from 100 to 1000
  model1.add(Dense(1000))
  # increase number of nodes from 100 to 1000
  model1.add(Dense(1000))
  # add new layer with 500 nodes
  model1.add(Dense(500))

  # unchanged
  model1.add(Dense(4, activation='softmax'))
  # unchanged
  model1.compile(loss = 'categorical_crossentropy',
              metrics = ['accuracy'],
              optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.001))

  return model1

def cnn_model_1b():
# this part to remain the same =====================================================================
  model1 = Sequential()
  model1.add(Conv2D(24, (4, 4), padding="same", input_shape=(48, 48, 1)))
  model1.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model1.add(Conv2D(48, (4, 4), padding="same"))
  model1.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model1.add(MaxPooling2D((3, 3)))
  model1.add(Flatten())
# this part to remain the same =====================================================================

  # same as previous model
  model1.add(Dense(1000))
  # same as previous model
  model1.add(Dense(1000))

  # add new layer with 1000 nodes
  model1.add(Dense(1000))
  # add new layer with 1000 nodes
  model1.add(Dense(1000))
  # add new layer with 1000 nodes
  model1.add(Dense(1000))
  # add new layer with 1000 nodes
  model1.add(Dense(1000))

  # same as previous model
  model1.add(Dense(500))

  # unchanged
  model1.add(Dense(4, activation='softmax'))
  # unchanged
  model1.compile(loss = 'categorical_crossentropy',
              metrics = ['accuracy'],
              optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.001))

  return model1

def cnn_model_1d():
# this part to remain the same =====================================================================
  model1 = Sequential()
  model1.add(Conv2D(24, (4, 4), padding="same", input_shape=(48, 48, 1)))
  model1.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model1.add(Conv2D(48, (4, 4), padding="same"))
  model1.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model1.add(MaxPooling2D((3, 3)))
  model1.add(Flatten())
# this part to remain the same =====================================================================

  # increase nodes from 2000 to 5000
  model1.add(Dense(5000))
  # increase nodes from 2000 to 5000
  model1.add(Dense(5000))
  # increase nodes from 2000 to 5000
  model1.add(Dense(5000))
  # increase nodes from 2000 to 5000
  model1.add(Dense(5000))
  ## increase nodes from 2000 to 5000
  model1.add(Dense(5000))
  # increase nodes from 1000 to 2000
  model1.add(Dense(2000))
  # increase nodes from 1000 to 2000
  model1.add(Dense(2000))
  # increase nodes from 1000 to 2000
  model1.add(Dense(2000))
  # increase nodes from 1000 to 2000
  model1.add(Dense(2000))

  # same as previous model
  model1.add(Dense(1000))

  #add drop out layer to (hopefully) help reduce overfitting
  model1.add(Dropout(.5))

  # same as previous model
  model1.add(Dense(500))
  # unchanged
  model1.add(Dense(4, activation='softmax'))
  # unchanged
  model1.compile(loss = 'categorical_crossentropy',
              metrics = ['accuracy'],
              optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.001))

  return model1

Observations:

  • this is our largest NN and, interestingly, performance has not improved
  • it seems by adding nodes/layers we are simply increasing the level of complexity to get similar results
  • the current model is substantially slower to train (and requires much more memory) but shows no signs of improved performance, so a simpler model will likely be a better base model to work with
  • since cnn_model_1a showed the best performance on the test data, let's go back to that model and see fi we can improve it

cnn_model_1a2¶

In [ ]:
def cnn_model_1a2():
# this part to remain the same =====================================================================
  model1 = Sequential()
  model1.add(Conv2D(24, (4, 4), padding="same", input_shape=(48, 48, 1)))
  model1.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model1.add(Conv2D(48, (4, 4), padding="same"))
  model1.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model1.add(MaxPooling2D((3, 3)))
  model1.add(Flatten())
# ^this part to remain the same ^ ==================================================================

  # change activaiton to relu
  model1.add(Dense(1000, activation = 'relu'))

  #add a dropout layer
  model1.add(Dropout(.2))

  #change activation to relu
  model1.add(Dense(1000, activation = 'relu'))

  #add a dropout layer
  model1.add(Dropout(.2))

  #change activaiton to relu
  model1.add(Dense(500, activation = 'relu'))

  #add a dropout layer
  model1.add(Dropout(.2))

  # unchanged
  model1.add(Dense(4, activation='softmax'))
  # unchanged
  model1.compile(loss = 'categorical_crossentropy',
              metrics = ['accuracy'],
              optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.001))

  return model1

Define Base Model¶

In [ ]:
# storing the base model for easy access
def get_base_model(shape_of_input):

  model1 = Sequential(name = 'BASE_MODEL')
  model1.add(Dense(1000, activation = 'relu', input_shape = shape_of_input))
  model1.add(Dropout(.2))
  model1.add(Dense(1000, activation = 'relu'))
  model1.add(Dropout(.2))
  model1.add(Dense(500, activation = 'relu'))
  model1.add(Dropout(.2))
  model1.add(Dense(4, activation='softmax'))

  return model1

Creating the second Convolutional Neural Network¶

  • Here we will trial different convolutional networks to feed into our base network (from model 1b)
In [ ]:
def cnn_model_2(shape_of_input):
  model = Sequential()
  model.add(Conv2D(24, (4, 4), padding="same", input_shape = shape_of_input))
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(Conv2D(48, (4, 4), padding="same"))
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(MaxPooling2D((3, 3)))

  model.add(Conv2D(24, (4, 4), padding="same"))
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(Conv2D(48, (4, 4), padding="same"))
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(MaxPooling2D((3, 3)))

  model.add(Flatten())

  ### BASE MODEL ###
  model.add(get_base_model((None, 1200)))


  # Compile model
  model.compile(loss = 'categorical_crossentropy',
              metrics = ['accuracy'],
              optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.001))

  return model

Observations and Insights: cnn_model_2

  • while the model is still overfit to the training data, this is the grayscale model is the best model we have seen yet!
  • let's add to (and subtract from) our convolutional network to see how it impacts performnce

Adjusting the Convolutional Neural Network¶

In [ ]:
def cnn_model_2a(shape_of_input):
  # Intializing a sequential model
  model_2 = Sequential()

  # Adding first conv layer with 16 filters and kernel size 3x3 , padding 'same,' provides the output size same as the input size
  model_2.add(Conv2D(3, (3, 3), padding="same", input_shape=shape_of_input))
  # Adding LeakyRelu activation function with a slope of 0.1
  model_2.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  # Adding second conv layer with 32 filters and kernel size 3x3 , padding 'same'
  model_2.add(Conv2D(48, (3, 3), padding="same"))
  # Adding another LeakyRelu activation function with a slope of 0.1
  model_2.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  # Adding max pooling layer
  model_2.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(4, 4)))
  # Add batch normalization layer
  model_2.add(BatchNormalization())
  # Adding third conv layer with 32 filters and kernel size 3x3 , padding 'same'
  model_2.add(Conv2D(48, (4, 4), padding="same"))
  # Adding another LeakyRelu activation function with a slope of 0.1
  model_2.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  # Adding fourth conv layer with 64 filters and kernel size 3x3 , padding 'same'
  model_2.add(Conv2D(96, (5, 5), padding="same"))
  # Adding another LeakyRelu activation function with a slope of 0.1
  model_2.add(Dropout(.4))
  # Adding max pooling layer
  model_2.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(4, 4)))
  # Add batch normalization layer
  model_2.add(BatchNormalization())
  # flattening the output of the conv layer after max pooling to make it ready for creating dense connections
  model_2.add(Flatten())

  ### BASE MODEL ###
  model_2.add(get_base_model((None, 864)))

  # Compile model
  model_2.compile(loss = 'categorical_crossentropy',
              metrics = ['accuracy'],
              optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.00001))

  return model_2

def cnn_model_2b(shape_of_input):
  # Intializing a sequential model
  model_2 = Sequential()

  # Adding first conv layer with 16 filters and kernel size 3x3 , padding 'same,' provides the output size same as the input size
  model_2.add(Conv2D(48, (3, 3), padding="same", input_shape=shape_of_input))
  # Adding LeakyRelu activation function with a slope of 0.1
  model_2.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  # Adding second conv layer with 32 filters and kernel size 3x3 , padding 'same'
  model_2.add(Conv2D(48, (3, 3), padding="same"))
  # Adding another LeakyRelu activation function with a slope of 0.1
  model_2.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  # Adding max pooling layer
  model_2.add(Conv2D(48, (3, 3), padding="same"))
  # Adding another LeakyRelu activation function with a slope of 0.1
  model_2.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  # Adding max pooling layer
  model_2.add(Conv2D(48, (3, 3), padding="same"))
  # Adding another LeakyRelu activation function with a slope of 0.1
  model_2.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  # Adding max pooling layer
  model_2.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(4, 4)))
  # Add batch normalization layer
  model_2.add(BatchNormalization())
  # Adding third conv layer with 32 filters and kernel size 3x3 , padding 'same'
  model_2.add(Conv2D(48, (4, 4), padding="same"))
  # Adding another LeakyRelu activation function with a slope of 0.1
  model_2.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  # Adding fourth conv layer with 64 filters and kernel size 3x3 , padding 'same'
  model_2.add(Conv2D(96, (5, 5), padding="same"))
  # Adding another LeakyRelu activation function with a slope of 0.1
  model_2.add(Conv2D(96, (5, 5), padding="same"))
  # Adding another LeakyRelu activation function with a slope of 0.1
  model_2.add(Conv2D(96, (5, 5), padding="same"))
  # Adding another LeakyRelu activation function with a slope of 0.1
  model_2.add(Dropout(.4))
  # Adding max pooling layer
  # Adding third conv layer with 32 filters and kernel size 3x3 , padding 'same'
  model_2.add(Conv2D(48, (4, 4), padding="same"))
  # Adding another LeakyRelu activation function with a slope of 0.1
  model_2.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  # Adding fourth conv layer with 64 filters and kernel size 3x3 , padding 'same'
  model_2.add(Conv2D(96, (5, 5), padding="same"))
  # Adding another LeakyRelu activation function with a slope of 0.1
  model_2.add(Conv2D(48, (4, 4), padding="same"))
  # Adding another LeakyRelu activation function with a slope of 0.1
  model_2.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  # Adding fourth conv layer with 64 filters and kernel size 3x3 , padding 'same'
  model_2.add(Conv2D(48, (4, 4), padding="same"))
  # Adding another LeakyRelu activation function with a slope of 0.1
  model_2.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  # Adding fourth conv layer with 64 filters and kernel size 3x3 , padding 'same'
  model_2.add(Dropout(.4))
  # Adding max pooling layer
  model_2.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(4, 4)))
  # Add batch normalization layer
  model_2.add(BatchNormalization())

  # flattening the output of the conv layer after max pooling to make it ready for creating dense connections
  model_2.add(Flatten())

  ### BASE MODEL ###
  model_2.add(get_base_model((None, 432)))

  # Compile model
  model_2.compile(loss = 'categorical_crossentropy',
              metrics = ['accuracy'],
              optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.00001))

  return model_2

Think About It:¶

  • Did the models have a satisfactory performance? If not, then what are the possible reasons?
  • Which Color mode showed better overall performance? What are the possible reasons? Do you think having 'rgb' color mode is needed because the images are already black and white?

Responses:

  • I am not satisfied with the results we have seen so far. We have a good starting point (cnn_model_2_G), but the model still needs substantial improvement.
  • In general the models working with grayscale images appear to do slightly better, but only slightly. Since the models working with RGB images are given every pixel value 3 times, it's possible that the excess data causes the model to be a little more overfit

Transfer Learning Architectures¶

In this section, we will create several Transfer Learning architectures. For the pre-trained models, we will select three popular architectures namely, VGG16, ResNet v2, and Efficient Net. The difference between these architectures and the previous architectures is that these will require 3 input channels while the earlier ones worked on 'grayscale' images. Therefore, we need to create new DataLoaders.

Creating our Data Loaders for Transfer Learning Architectures¶

In this section, we are creating data loaders that we will use as inputs to our Neural Network. We will have to go with color_mode = 'rgb' as this is the required format for the transfer learning architectures.

In [ ]:
# nothing needs to be done here
# Because of the way we created our previous loaders we can simply utilize our RGB datasets

Model Building¶

  • Import VGG16 upto the layer of your choice and add Fully Connected layers on top of it.
In [ ]:
# Getting only the conv layers for transfer learning.
transfer_layer = imported_model_VGG16.get_layer('block5_pool')
vgg_conv_layers = Model(inputs=imported_model_VGG16.input, outputs=transfer_layer.output)

# make sure pre-trained layers will not be trained
vgg_conv_layers.trainable=False
In [ ]:
def cnn_model_VGG():
  # Intializing a sequential model
  model = Sequential()

  model.add(vgg_conv_layers)
  model.add(Flatten())

  ### BASE MODEL ###
  model.add(get_base_model((None, 512)))

  # Compile model
  model.compile(loss = 'categorical_crossentropy',
              metrics = ['accuracy'],
              optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.001))

  return model

Think About It:

  • What do you infer from the general trend in the training performance?
  • Is the training accuracy consistently improving?
  • Is the validation accuracy also improving similarly?

Responses:

  • this model is not especially good at identify facial expreions, but not significantly wore than other models we have tests
  • training accuracy improves over the first 50 epochs
  • validation accuracy does not seem to improve beyond 10 epochs, suggesting that the model is simply learning to overfit the training data

Observations and Insights: cnn_model_VGG

  • the model is not substantially better than other models we have tested, and it is meaningfully worse than the current best model, cnn_model_2_G
  • let's try utiliing other pre-trained models and see how they perform

Note: You can even go back and build your own architecture on top of the VGG16 Transfer layer and see if you can improve the performance

In [ ]:
# Getting only the conv layers for transfer learning.
transfer_layer = imported_model_Resnet.get_layer('conv5_block3_out')
resnet_conv_layers = Model(inputs=imported_model_Resnet.input, outputs=transfer_layer.output)

# make sure pre-trained layers will not be trained
resnet_conv_layers.trainable=False
In [ ]:
def cnn_model_Resnet():
  # Intializing a sequential model
  model = Sequential()

  model.add(resnet_conv_layers)

  model.add(Flatten())

  ### BASE MODEL ###
  model.add(get_base_model((None, 8192)))

  # Compile model
  model.compile(loss = 'categorical_crossentropy',
              metrics = ['accuracy'],
              optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.001))

  return model

Observations and Insights: cnn_model_Resnet

  • This model has performed very poorly
  • accuracy on th training data never exceeds .3
  • accuracy on the validation data oscilates between about .3 and .275
  • the "learnings" from the model's previous training does not carry over to our use case

Note: You can even go back and build your own architecture on top of the ResNet Transfer layer and see if you can improve the performance.

Model Building¶

  • Import EfficientNet upto the layer of your choice and add Fully Connected layers on top of it.
In [ ]:
# Getting only the conv layers for transfer learning.
transfer_layer = imported_model_EfficientNet.get_layer('top_activation')
efficientNet_conv_layers = Model(inputs=imported_model_EfficientNet.input, outputs=transfer_layer.output)

# make sure pre-trained layers will not be trained
efficientNet_conv_layers.trainable=False
In [ ]:
def cnn_model_EffNet():
  # Intializing a sequential model
  model = Sequential()

  model.add(efficientNet_conv_layers)

  model.add(Flatten())

  ### BASE MODEL ###
  model.add(get_base_model((None, 5632)))

  # Compile model
  model.compile(loss = 'categorical_crossentropy',
              metrics = ['accuracy'],
              optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.001))

  return model

Observations and Insights: cnn_model_EffNet

  • performance looks very similar to the Resnet model's performance
  • training accuracy remains below .3
  • avlidation accuracy oscillates between about .3 and .275
  • again, the "learnings" or the model's previous training do not carry over to our use case

Note: You can even go back and build your own architecture on top of the VGG16 Transfer layer and see if you can improve the performance.

Think About It:

  • What is your overall performance of these Transfer Learning Architectures? Can we draw a comparison of these models' performances. Are we satisfied with the accuracies that we have received?
  • Do you think our issue lies with 'rgb' color_mode?

Responses:

  • in general Transfer learning architectures did not perform well
  • it seems that the models are trained for specific tasks and are not equipped to identify facial expressions
  • it seems doubtful to me that the problem lies with the RGB color mode. If this were the case our own RGB models woud likely have performed substantially worse

Now that we have tried multiple pre-trained models, let's build a complex CNN architecture and see if we can get better performance.

Building a Complex Neural Network Architecture¶

In this section, we will build a more complex Convolutional Neural Network Model that has close to as many parameters as we had in our Transfer Learning Models. However, we will have only 1 input channel for our input images.

Creating our Data Loaders¶

In this section, we are creating data loaders which we will use as inputs to the more Complicated Convolutional Neural Network. We will go ahead with color_mode = 'grayscale'.

In [ ]:
# the needed data loaders have already been created

Model Building¶

  • Try building a layer with 5 Convolutional Blocks and see if performance increases.
In [ ]:
def cnn_model_3():
  model = Sequential()

  model.add(Conv2D(64, (2, 2), padding="same", input_shape = (48,48,1), activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Conv2D(128, (2, 2), padding="same", activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Conv2D(512, (2, 2), padding="same", activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Conv2D(512, (2, 2), padding="same", activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Conv2D(128, (2, 2), padding="same", activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Flatten())

  ### BASE MODEL ###
  model.add(get_base_model((None, 128)))


  # Compile model
  model.compile(loss = 'categorical_crossentropy',
              metrics = ['accuracy'],
              optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.001))

  return model

Adjusting the Model¶

In [ ]:
def cnn_model_3a():
  model = Sequential()

  model.add(Conv2D(64, (2, 2), padding="same", input_shape = (48,48,1), activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Conv2D(128, (2, 2), padding="same", activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Conv2D(512, (2, 2), padding="same", activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Conv2D(512, (2, 2), padding="same", activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Conv2D(128, (2, 2), padding="same", activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Flatten())

  model.add(Dense(256, activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Dense(512, activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Dense(4, activation='softmax'))


  # Compile model
  model.compile(loss = 'categorical_crossentropy',
              metrics = ['accuracy'],
              optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.001))

  return model

cnn_model_3b¶

In [ ]:
def cnn_model_3b():
  model = Sequential()

  model.add(Conv2D(64, (2, 2), padding="same", input_shape = (48,48,1), activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Conv2D(128, (2, 2), padding="same", activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Conv2D(512, (2, 2), padding="same", activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Conv2D(512, (2, 2), padding="same", activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Conv2D(128, (2, 2), padding="same", activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Flatten())

  model.add(Dense(256, activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Dense(512, activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  #adding additional layers
  model.add(Dense(512, activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Dense(512, activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Dense(512, activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Dense(512, activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Dense(512, activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Dense(256, activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Dense(4, activation='softmax'))


  # Compile model
  model.compile(loss = 'categorical_crossentropy',
              metrics = ['accuracy'],
              optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.001))

  return model

def cnn_model_3c():
  model = Sequential()

  model.add(Conv2D(64, (2, 2), padding="same", input_shape = (48,48,1), activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  #model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Conv2D(128, (2, 2), padding="same", activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
 # model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Conv2D(512, (2, 2), padding="same", activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  #model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Conv2D(512, (2, 2), padding="same", activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  #new layer
  model.add(Conv2D(1024, (2, 2), padding="same", activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  # #new layer
  model.add(Conv2D(512, (2, 2), padding="same", activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Dense(512, activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Dense(512, activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  #new layer
  model.add(Dense(1024, activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  #new layer

  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  #new layer

  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))

Observations: cnn_model_3c

  • the additional epochs made a considerable difference! With an accuracy of about 75% on the test data, this is the best model yet, and it may still be showing signs of generalized learning. However, for the considerable training time required this model may not be the best to explore further
  • cnn_model_3b was almost as good, but was much quicker to train, so it might be a better alterntive for further exploration
  • we will utilize the ANN portion of cnn_model_3b for one last set of test models...

Repurposing the architectures from the tranfer learning models¶

Here we will utilize the convolutional networks from the transfer learning models, but this time we will train them on our data to see how they perform (we will set the 'trainable' parameter equal to true). We will use the base model from cnn_model_2b to add the CNNs to

In [ ]:
# define new base model - this is the base model from cnn_model_2b
def get_base_model_2():
  model = Sequential()
  model.add(Dense(256, activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))
  model.add(Dense(512, activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))
  model.add(Dense(512, activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))
  model.add(Dense(512, activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))
  model.add(Dense(512, activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))
  model.add(Dense(512, activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))
  model.add(Dense(512, activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))
  model.add(Dense(256, activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))
  model.add(Dense(4, activation='softmax'))

  return model

Repurposing VGG16's Architecture¶

In [ ]:
# import the model
imported_model_VGG16 = VGG16(weights='imagenet',include_top = False, input_shape = (48,48,3))

# Getting only the conv layers for transfer learning.
transfer_layer = imported_model_VGG16.get_layer('block5_pool')
vgg_conv_layers = Model(inputs=imported_model_VGG16.input, outputs=transfer_layer.output)

# make sure pre-trained layers WILL be trained on our data
vgg_conv_layers.trainable=True

Downloading data from https://storage.googleapis.com/tensorflow/keras-applications/vgg16/vgg16_weights_tf_dim_ordering_tf_kernels_notop.h5
58889256/58889256 [==============================] - 3s 0us/step
In [ ]:
def cnn_model_VGG_2():
  # Intializing a sequential model
  model = Sequential()

  model.add(vgg_conv_layers)
  model.add(Flatten())

  ### BASE MODEL ###
  model.add(get_base_model_2())

  # Compile model
  model.compile(loss = 'categorical_crossentropy',
              metrics = ['accuracy'],
              optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.001))

  return model
In [ ]:
#load/compile model

#train model

Repurposing ResNet's Architecture¶

In [ ]:
#import model architecture
imported_model_Resnet = ap.ResNet101(include_top = False, weights = "imagenet", input_shape=(48,48,3))

# Getting only the conv layers for transfer learning.
transfer_layer = imported_model_Resnet.get_layer('conv5_block3_out')
resnet_conv_layers = Model(inputs=imported_model_Resnet.input, outputs=transfer_layer.output)

# make sure pre-trained layers WILL be trained on our data
resnet_conv_layers.trainable=True
In [ ]:
def cnn_model_Resnet_2():
  # Intializing a sequential model
  model = Sequential()

  model.add(resnet_conv_layers)

  model.add(Flatten())

  ### BASE MODEL ###
  model.add(get_base_model_2())

  # Compile model
  model.compile(loss = 'categorical_crossentropy',
              metrics = ['accuracy'],
              optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.001))

  return model
In [ ]:
#load/compile model

cnn_history_ResNet_2 = train_model( cnn_model_ResNet_2, 40, 'RGB')

Repurposing the EfficientNet Architecture¶

In [ ]:
#import the EfficientNet model
imported_model_EfficientNet = ap.EfficientNetV2B2(include_top=False,weights="imagenet", input_shape= (48, 48, 3))

# Getting only the conv layers for transfer learning.
transfer_layer = imported_model_EfficientNet.get_layer('top_activation')
efficientNet_conv_layers = Model(inputs=imported_model_EfficientNet.input, outputs=transfer_layer.output)

# make sure pre-trained layers WILL be trained on our data
efficientNet_conv_layers.trainable=True

Final Model (Milestone)¶

Plotting the Confusion Matrix for the chosen final model¶

cnn_model_3c is the best model we have been able to produce, achieving an accuracy of about 75% on the test data

In [ ]:
# test model to get y_test_arg and y_pred_arg variables
y_pred=cnn_model_3c_gen2.predict(x_test_norm_GRAY)
y_pred_arg=np.argmax(y_pred,axis=1)
y_test_arg=np.argmax(y_test_encoded,axis=1)

# Plotting the Confusion Matrix
confusion_matrix = tf.math.confusion_matrix(y_test_arg,y_pred_arg)

)

4/4 [==============================] - 0s 31ms/step

Observations and Insights:

  • sad and neutral seem to be the most difficult emotions to correctly identify, the most common mistake is for the model to get these two emotions confused
  • this refects the lower recall, precision and f-1 scores the model has on neutral and sad categories

Milestone Conclusions¶

Milestone Insights¶

Refined insights:¶

What are the most meaningful insights from the data relevant to the problem?

  • None of our models were able to exceed 75% accuracy on the test data, none of our models hit 75% accuracy on the validation data. Any model that makes it close to 70% accurcy on the validation data seems to stop learning (they will overfit the data, but validation accuracy does not improve)
  • this could mean that 25%-30% of faces in our validation data contain features that are not adequately represented in the training data
  • alternatively, it could men there is a problem with our data sets
  • we removed images that had exact duplicates, but similar images (ones that differ by even just one pixel) could still remain in our datasets (which could result in biases or information leakage)
  • additionally, there could be mislabeled images which would impact perforance negatively
  • if there are any issues with the datasets, fixing such problems could substantially improve model accuracy going forward, this is a matter that is definitely worth exploring further

Comparison of various techniques and their relative performance:¶

How do different techniques perform? Which one is performing relatively better? Is there scope to improve the performance further?

  • There is almost certainly scope to improve the model. I have only scratched the surface of all the possible architectures that could be created, and seemingly small changes can have substantial impact to perforance
  • the best technique seems to be creating smaller sub-structures and add such structures on top of one another. A well designed layer repeated a few times seems to beat out a large, but unsophisticted model (ie. one with only a lot of nodes and dense layers)
  • BatchNormalization, leakyRelu and dropout layers, seem to go a long way when sprinkled in throughout the model layers (instead of just adding them at the end of the model)
  • Transfer learning was not a good strategy as it seems the models were designed and trained for specific purposes (purposes which do not align with the problem of facial expression recognition)
  • it mkes sense to purpuse designing our own model because we can design and tweak it to meet the needs specific for our task

Proposal for the final solution design:¶

What model do you propose to be adopted? Why is this the best solution to adopt?

  • cnn_model_3c should be adopted because it is the model which has achieved the highest accurcies on the validation and test data. The model is already large enough that training it has become cumbersome, so, going forward, it may make more sense to lessen the complexity of the model in order to make it more efficient. However, since the model only needs to be trained prior to being deployed, the amount of time to train the model need not be taken into account when considering which to deploy.
  • for the most part, cnn_model_3c used two different "sub-structures" and simply repeated these structures with minor tweaks (usually tweaking the number of nodes), while this approch has proven effective, there are all sorts of sub-structures that should be explored. It is very possible that the final model could look substantially different from the current version if a different sub-structures are found to be more promising than the ones used in cnn_model_3c
  • most of the experimentation revolved around manipulating network architecture, hyperparameters were not relly explored. Now that we have a few decent models to use as a starting point further exploration of hyperparameters should occur

Refining cnn_model_3c (cnn_model_3c2)¶

cnn_model_3c is very large and takes a long time to train, the model can likely be simplified and improved

In [ ]:
def cnn_model_3c2():
  model = Sequential()

  model.add(Conv2D(64, (2, 2), padding="same", input_shape = (48,48,1), activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  #model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  #decreased # of filters
  model.add(Conv2D(64, (2, 2), padding="same", activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
 # model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

#decreased # of filters
  model.add(Conv2D(128, (2, 2), padding="same", activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  #model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

#decreased # of filters
  model.add(Conv2D(128, (2, 2), padding="same", activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  #decreased # of filters
  model.add(Conv2D(256, (2, 2), padding="same", activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  #decreased # of filters
  model.add(Conv2D(256, (2, 2), padding="same", activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Conv2D(128, (2, 2), padding="same", activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Flatten())

  model.add(Dense(256, activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Dense(512, activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Dense(512, activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

#removed 5 'substructures,' 3 with 1024 nodes, 2 with 512 nodes

  model.add(Dense(512, activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Dense(512, activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Dense(256, activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Dense(4, activation='softmax'))


  # Compile model
  model.compile(loss = 'categorical_crossentropy',
              metrics = ['accuracy'],
              optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.001))

  return model

Observations: cnn_model_3c2

  • This model is a meaningful improvement upon cnn_model_3c. Not only is it substantially faster to train, it has also achieved the highest accuracies on the test data yet.
  • Based on the confusion matrix, we can see that the model has a tendancy to mistake sad photos for neutral photos
  • Based on the plot of the training vs validation accuracies we can once again see clear "wall" around 75% accuracy which our models have not been able to exceed...why is it that all of our models have such difficulty with around 25% of the data?
  • let's explore this in more depth to see if there is, indeed, some issue with our datasets (like mislabeled or very similar images)

Utilizing a different dataset¶

If there is some issue with our datasets causing a systematic inability to exceed about 75% accuracy, using a different dataset should resolve the issue let's see how our model performs when trained on a different set of images.

  • the new datasets to be used were obtained from https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/msambare/fer2013 (we will not utilize the fear, disgust or anger images from the dataset)
In [ ]:
# Storing the path of the data file from the Google drive
folder_path = '/content/drive/MyDrive/MIT_DataScience/Capstone Project/Secondary Dataset/'
In [ ]:
# create dataframe to store images and relevant features
image_df_2 = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['emotion', 'data type', 'path', 'image','image hash','pixel data rgb','pixel data gray'])

counter = 0

data_type_path = os.listdir(folder_path)

# get each data type folder (ie. training, validation, test)
for data_type in data_type_path:
  emotion_type_path = os.listdir(folder_path + data_type )
  # get each emotion type folder (ie. happy, sad, neutral, surprise)
  for emotion in emotion_type_path:
    image_path = os.listdir(folder_path +  data_type + '/' + emotion)
    for face_image in image_path:
      # get the path for an individual image
      path_of_image = folder_path + data_type +'/'+  emotion + '/' + face_image

      # load the image, as color and grayscale image
      img_rgb = load_img(folder_path + data_type +'/'+  emotion + '/' + face_image, color_mode='rgb')
      img_gray = load_img(folder_path + data_type +'/'+  emotion + '/' + face_image, color_mode='grayscale')

      # this will assign a unique hash to every image (which we will use to check for duplicates)
      image_hash = imagehash.average_hash(img_gray)

      #convert color and grayscale images into separate pixel arrays
      pixel_array_rgb = img_to_array(img_rgb)
      pixel_array_gray = img_to_array(img_gray)

      # add path, emotion type and data type into a dataframe
      image_df_2 = image_df_2.append({'emotion' : emotion, 'data type' : data_type, 'path' : path_of_image,"image":img_rgb,'image hash':image_hash, 'pixel data rgb':pixel_array_rgb, 'pixel data gray':pixel_array_gray},ignore_index = True)

# get datasets from respective dataframes/columns and convert data to a nummpy array for simplified usage and proper shape
x_train_2 = []
x_val_2 = []

for image in train_data_df_2['pixel data gray']:
  x_train_2.append(image)

for image in validation_data_df_2['pixel data gray']:
  x_val_2.append(image)

x_train_2 = np.array(x_train_2)
x_val_2 = np.array(x_val_2)

print("x_train_2 shape:",x_train_2.shape)
print("x_val_2 shape:",x_val_2.shape)

  y_train_encoded_2[i] = emotion_dict.get(y_train_encoded_2[i])

for i in range(0,len(y_val_encoded_2)):
  y_val_encoded_2[i] = emotion_dict.get(y_val_encoded_2[i])

In [ ]:
# let's check for overlap (duplicate images) between the training data of our new datast and our original test data
image_hash_train = train_data_df_2['image hash'].to_frame() # image hash column of original image_df
image_hash_test = test_data_df['image hash'].to_frame() #image hash of our original test dataframe
unionData = image_hash_test.merge(image_hash_train, how = 'inner' ,indicator=False)
print(unionData.shape)

(109, 1)

Observations: cnn_model_3c2 on alternative dataset

  • we observed the same phenomenon while training the model on a new dataset, accuracy on the validation data maxed out around 75% while accuracy on the training data continued to improve
  • this gives me greater confidence that about 25% of images are simply more difficult to classify (as opposed to there being something systematically wrong with our data)
  • we saw very favorable accuracy when testing the model on the test data, but it turns out this number is misleading as almost all of the test images are contained within the training data of the new dataset!
  • let's see if if adding depth to our CNN (ie adding convolutional layers) can continue to improve our model

Deminishing Return on Architecture Complexity (cnn_model_3c3)¶

In [ ]:
def cnn_model_3c3():
  model = Sequential()

  #let's repeat each layer but increase the dropout rate to see if we can prevent the divergence between validation and training accuracies

  model.add(Conv2D(64, (2, 2), padding="same", input_shape = (48,48,1), activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  #model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

## duplicate substructure
  model.add(Conv2D(64, (2, 2), padding="same", activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  #model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Conv2D(64, (2, 2), padding="same", activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  # model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

## duplicate substructure
  model.add(Conv2D(64, (2, 2), padding="same", activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  # model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Conv2D(128, (2, 2), padding="same", activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  #model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

## duplicate substructure
  model.add(Conv2D(128, (2, 2), padding="same", activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  #model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Conv2D(128, (2, 2), padding="same", activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

## duplicate substructure
  model.add(Conv2D(128, (2, 2), padding="same", activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Conv2D(256, (2, 2), padding="same", activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

## duplicate substructure
  model.add(Conv2D(256, (2, 2), padding="same", activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Conv2D(256, (2, 2), padding="same", activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

## dupicate substructure
  model.add(Conv2D(256, (2, 2), padding="same", activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  # model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Conv2D(128, (2, 2), padding="same", activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  # model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

## duplicate substructure
  model.add(Conv2D(128, (2, 2), padding="same", activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  # model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Flatten())  ## =================================== FLATTEN LAYER ===

  model.add(Dense(256, activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Dense(512, activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Dense(512, activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Dense(512, activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Dense(512, activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Dense(256, activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(Dropout(.2))

  model.add(Dense(4, activation='softmax'))


  # Compile model
  model.compile(loss = 'categorical_crossentropy',
              metrics = ['accuracy'],
              optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.001))

  return model

Observations: cnn_model_3c3

  • once again we observe a divergence in training vs vaidation accuracy once validation accuracy hits about 70%
  • the model showed a slight improvement in accuracy on the test data, but suffered from meaningfully more complexity from increased layers (which resulted in meaningfully slower training times)
  • After doubling the number of convolutional 'substructures' we only saw a 1% improvement in accuracy, so we seem to be reaching a point of deminishing return based on architectural changes alone. It seems like our time will be better spent tweaking other aspects of our model
  • we will continue to work with cnn_model_3c2 as it was very similar performance-wise but much faster to train
  • we should experiment with model hyperparameters, but first let's apply some image augmentation to add to our data set (and hopefully improve generalized learning and break through this 70% - 75% accuracy wall we keep running into)

Observations: cnn_model_3c2 w/ data augmentation

  • augmenting the data gave us enough lift to get the model's accuracy on the test data above 80%!
  • this strongly suggests that our model would benefit substantially from more images, specifically from a more diverse array of emotion examples
  • this makes sense as each emotion has a diverse number of appearances, with more images the more of these appearances we will be able to capture while training our models
